    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/09-rag-retrieval/05-advanced-rag.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Naive top-k RAG breaks on multi-hop questions because the retriever cannot know which chunks are relevant until it has already partially answered the question; the final sub-query often has zero semantic overlap with the original.; GraphRAG separates indexing granularity from retrieval granularity: an LLM extracts entities/relations, community detection clusters them hierarchically, and community summaries let global questions be answered without stuffing hundreds of chunks into context.; Multi-hop / iterative retrieval solves the dependency chain by looping retrieve -> reason -> reformulate, where each retrieval's result seeds the next query until the model decides it has enough.; Contextual retrieval fixes chunk decontextualisation: an isolated chunk embeds into the wrong neighbourhood; prepending an LLM-generated context sentence pushes its embedding toward the query's neighbourhood.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  advrag-multihop-vs-singleshot, advrag-contextual-retrieval-embedding-shift\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
