    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/11-evaluation/04-reasoning-coding-agentic-evals.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: A single generation conflates intrinsic ability with sampling luck; Pass@k reframes coding ability as a probability, and the unbiased estimator is a sampling-without-replacement counting argument: 1 - C(n-c,k)/C(n,k) is the chance that a random draw of k from the n generated samples contains ZERO of the c passers.; The naive estimator 1-(1-c/n)^k overestimates Pass@k for small n, and Pass@k can DECREASE as k grows toward n when a problem has c=0 (no passers to ever draw).; Ground truth for code is behavior, not text: correctness must be verified by RUNNING the code, and running untrusted model code demands an isolation broker (Docker/gVisor/Firecracker) with resource caps.; Math answers need symbolic equivalence, not string match ('1/2' == '0.5'); and formal-proof benchmarks sidestep equivalence heuristics entirely because a proof assistant's kernel either type-checks the proof or it does not.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  rcae-passk-urn-without-replacement, rcae-accuracy-vs-compute-crossing-curves\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
